    "content_hash": "sha256:559c91df2fd7618ffeb92a35c9eb7e504e499ed7b0998e292d71fa280e2c9cf5",
    "summary": "Timur (Tamerlane, 1336–1405 AD) was the last great nomadic conqueror, a Turkic-Mongol ruler from the [[event:2307|Chagatai Khanate]] region who built an empire stretching from Turkey to India through thirty-five years of devastating military campaigns, claiming to be restoring the [[event:91|Mongol Empire]] of Genghis Khan while simultaneously presenting himself as a champion of Sunni Islam. Timur conquered his way across Central Asia, Persia, the Caucasus, northern India (sacking Delhi in 1398), Syria (sacking Damascus and Aleppo), and Anatolia — where he [[event:2277|defeated and captured the Ottoman Sultan Bayezid I]] at Ankara in 1402, temporarily halting the Ottoman advance into Europe.\n\nTimur's conquests were marked by extreme violence calibrated as terror: he erected towers of skulls outside conquered cities and massacred populations that resisted. Isfahan's population was reportedly slaughtered after a tax revolt, with 70,000 skulls used to build towers. Delhi's sack resulted in a massacre of 100,000 prisoners and left the city so devastated it took a century to recover. The [[event:2228|Mongols' destruction of Baghdad]] had eliminated the eastern Islamic heartland; Timur's devastation of Delhi, Syria, and Anatolia further disrupted the recovery of Islamic civilization's core territories. Yet Timur's capital Samarkand (in modern Uzbekistan) became one of the most magnificent cities in the world — he forcibly relocated the finest craftsmen, architects, scholars, and artists from conquered cities to beautify his capital, producing the Registan complex and other Persian-Timurid architectural masterpieces. The Timurid cultural tradition he established influenced both Safavid Persian and Mughal Indian civilization.",
